<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="S_Parametric_Surfaces_Surface_Area">
  <title>Surfaces Defined Parametrically and Surface Area</title>
  <objectives>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            What is a parameterization of a surface?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            How do we find the surface area of a parametrically defined surface?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
  </objectives>
  <introduction component="instructor">
    <title>Notes to the Instructor and Dependencies</title>
    <p>
      
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Introduction</title>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-">
        <statement>
            <p>
                If a vertically simple region <m>D</m> can be described by the inequalities <m>a \leq x \leq b</m> and <m>g_1(x) \leq y \leq g_2(x)</m>, where <m>g_1(x)</m> and <m>g_2(x)</m> are functions of only <m>x</m>, then the double integral can be written as an iterated integral in the following way
                <md>
                \iint_D f(x,y) \, dA = \int_{x=a}^{x=b} \int_{y=g_1(x)}^{y=g_2(x)} f(x,y) \, dy \, dx
                </md>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Alternatively, if a horizontally simple region <m>D</m> is described by the inequalities <m>c \leq y \leq d</m> and <m>h_1(y) \leq x \leq h_2(y)</m>, where <m>h_1(y)</m> and <m>h_2(y)</m> are functions of only <m>y</m>, then the double integral can be written as an iterated integral in the following way
                <md>
                \iint_D f(x,y) \, dA = \int_{y=c}^{y=d} \int_{x=h_1(y)}^{x=h_2(y)} f(x,y) \, dx \, dy
                </md>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                We will make a brief argument using the classic calculus approach to give an outline for a proof of this result. We will visualize the double integral with a region similar to the one used in the Preview Activity, as shown in <xref ref="proof-DI"/>. Remember that we will have a region of integration given by the inequalities <m>a \leq x \leq b</m> and <m>g_1(x) \leq y \leq g_2(x)</m>, where <m>g_1(x)</m> and <m>g_2(x)</m> are functions of only <m>x</m>
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="proof-DI">
            <caption>The double integral <m>\iint_R f(x,y) dA</m> visualized as the volume between the <m>xy</m>-plane and the surface given by <m>z=f(x,y)</m>, shown in pink, over the region <M>R</m>, shown in blue</caption>
              <interactive label="interactive-proof-DI" platform="sage" width="91%" aspect="1:1">
                <description>
                  <p>Coordinate axes for <m>xyz</m>-space showing a solid region over the triangle with  vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>, <m>(1,0,0)</m>, and <m>(0,1,0)</m>.
                  </p>
                </description>
                <slate surface="sage">
                    var('t,s,x,y,z')
                    from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
                    scale=1.5; ao=0.5;aoff=0.25;
                    plot1=axes(scale,1,color="black",frame=False,aspect_ratio=1,opacity=ao)+text3d("x",(scale+aoff,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,scale+aoff,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,scale+aoff),fontsize=30)
                    f(x,y)=1-x^2-y^2
                    plot1+=parametric_plot3d((s,0,t*f(s,0)),(s,0,1),(t,0,1),color="gray",opacity=0.2)
                    plot1+=parametric_plot3d((0,s,t*f(0,s)),(s,0,1),(t,0,1),color="gray",opacity=0.2)
                    plot1+=parametric_plot3d((s,1-s,t*f(s,1-s)),(s,0,1),(t,0,1),color="gray",opacity=0.2)
                    plot1+=parametric_plot3d((s,t*(1-s),0),(s,0,1),(t,0,1),color="blue",opacity=0.6)
                    param(s,t)=(s,t*(1-s),f(s,t*(1-s)))
                    #set up grid      n is number of steps in s    m is number of steps in t  
                    #a1 is min s    a2 is max s   b1 is min t    b2 is max t
                    n=4;m=5;a1=0;a2=1;b1=0;b2=1; 
                    #c1 is surface color     o1 is surface opacity
                    #c2 and o2 are for constant t value traces
                    #c3 and o3 are for constant s value traces
                    c1="pink"; c2="black"; c3="black"; o1=0.6; o2=0.4; o3=0.4;
                    plot1+=parametric_plot3d(param,(s,a1,a2),(t,b1,b2),color=c1,opacity=o1)
                    for i in range(n+1):
                        sv=a1+i/n*(a2-a1)
                        plot1+=parametric_plot3d(param(sv,t),(t,b1,b2),color=c2,opacity=o2)
                    for i in range(m+1):
                        tv=b1+i/m*(b2-b1)
                        plot1+=parametric_plot3d(param(s,tv),(s,a1,a2),color=c3,opacity=o3)
                    show(plot1,viewpoint=[[-0.3349,-0.5276,-0.7807],127.28],camera_position=[4.2763,2.4643,2.3687])
                </slate>
              </interactive>
          </figure>
          <p>
            For Step 1 of the classic calculus approach, we will approximate this double integral with <m>n</m> prisms of equal width along constant values of <m>x</m> as shown in <xref ref="proof-approx"/>. The width of these <m>n</m> equal width prisms will be <m>\Delta x=\frac{b-a}{n}</m>. These prisms will involve the cross sectional area of our volume at the following values of <m>x</m>: <m>x_0=a,x_1=a+\Delta x, \ldots , x_i = a+i \Delta x, \ldots, x_{n-1}=a+(i-1)\Delta x</m>.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="proof-approx">
            <caption>The double integral <m>\iint_R f(x,y) dA</m> approximation with prisms along constant values of <m>x</m></caption>
              <interactive label="interactive-proof-approx" platform="sage" width="91%" aspect="1:1">
                <description>
                  <p>Coordinate axes for <m>xyz</m>-space showing a solid region over the triangle with  vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>, <m>(1,0,0)</m>, and <m>(0,1,0)</m>.
                  </p>
                </description>
                <slate surface="sage">
                    var('t,s,x,y,z')
                    from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
                    scale=1.5; ao=0.5;aoff=0.25;
                    plot1=axes(scale,1,color="black",aspect_ratio=1,frame=False,opacity=ao)+text3d("x",(scale+aoff,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,scale+aoff,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,scale+aoff),fontsize=30)
                    plot1+=polygon([(0,0,0),(0,1,0),(1,0,0)],color="blue",opacity=0.7)
                    f(x,y)=1-x^2-y^2
                    n=5
                    av=[i/n for i in range(n)]
                    da=1/n
                    for a in av:
                        plot1+=parametric_plot3d((a,t,s*f(a,t)),(s,0,1),(t,0,1-a),color="pink",opacity=0.4)
                        plot1+=parametric_plot3d((a+da,t,s*f(a,t)),(s,0,1),(t,0,1-a),color="pink",opacity=0.4)
                        plot1+=parametric_plot3d((a+s*da,t,0),(s,0,1),(t,0,1-a),color="pink",opacity=0.4)
                        plot1+=parametric_plot3d((a+s*da,0,t*f(a,0)),(s,0,1),(t,0,1),color="pink",opacity=0.4)
                        plot1+=parametric_plot3d((a+s*da,t,f(a,t)),(s,0,1),(t,0,1-a),color="pink",opacity=0.4)
                    show(plot1,viewpoint=[[-0.3349,-0.5276,-0.7807],127.28],camera_position=[4.2763,2.4643,2.3687])
                </slate>
              </interactive>
          </figure>
          <p>
            The cross sectional area of the volume at <m>x=a</m> will be given by 
            <md>CSA(a)=\int_{y=g_1(a)}^{y=g_2(a)} f(a,y) dy</md>. 
            Note that this takes the height of the surface on this slice and integrates over only the relevant range of <m>y</m>-values. Our approximation for Step 1 of the CCA will be given by
            <md>\iint_R f(x,y) dA \approx \Sum_{n=0}^{n-1} CSA(a) \Delta x</md> 
            Note that this approximation already accomplishes Step 2 of the CCA since a smaller scale means that we have an increase in <m>n</m> which decreases <m>\Delta x</m>. 
          </p>
          <p>
            Applying a limit in Step 3 of our approximation will yield
            <md> \iint_R f(x,y) dA =lim_{n\to \infty} \Sum_{n=0}^{n-1} CSA(x_i) \Delta x</md> 
            which you may recognize as a definite integral. In particular, 
            <md> \iint_R f(x,y) dA =\int_{x=a}^{x=b} CSA(x) dx</md> 
            which we can substitute in our expression for <m>CSA(x)</m> to get
            <md> \iint_R f(x,y) dA =\int_{x=a}^{x=b} \left[ \int_{y=g_1(x)}^{y=g_2(x)} f(x,y) dy \right] dx</md>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Note that when we substituted in our expression for the cross sectional area integral, we used the variable <m>x</m> since that corresponds to the value/variable used in the larger expression. The other result with prisms along constant values of <m>y</m> has a very analogous argument but does not offer any additional illumination, so we omit this discussion. 
          </p>
        </proof>    
    </proposition>
    
    </subsection>
</section>

